caption: Best all-you-can-eat in Chicago. 10/10. 5 star. Will come again. Have the miso soup after you've eaten all the sushi you can to relax your tummy a bit.

For what it's worth, Sushi Sai is a pretty good AYCE sushi place. I like that they're open all the way from lunch to the end of dinner so there's no rush to get there "early".  The menu is pretty standard with a variety of appetizers, simple and fancier rolls, and nigiri. I'd skip the apps altogether and just do sushi. The rolls come in 5 or 8 pieces depending whether they're larger or smaller. The only one I didn't like was the shrimp tempura since the tempura wasn't very fresh and the fried batter was kind of hard. For nigiri, salmon and yellowtail were pretty good but do be warned that the nigiris are large and come with a lot of rice.  Their fish quality is good, decently fresh but not amazing. For $22 a person, the AYCE is reasonably priced. I'd probably only come here for the AYCE.
Fair price and delicious but they ignore part of your order if they are not ready for it !!

Superb  sushi for a regular sushi place, and way way better than your typical ayce place—the nigiri sushi has pieces of fish that are large and overlap the rice, not the other way round. Quality is excellent as is the service. Would make this my regular place but I don’t live anywhere near Chicago.

Would recommend anything that doesn't have fried stuff. Great casual sushi spot.

Sushi enthusiast here!  It's currently $20 for an all-you-can-eat lunch/dinner experience, and it's totally worth it! Any sushi place will cost more than $20 after the first specialty roll, and I got four specialty rolls and ten pieces of sushi (meat and rice only). You have to eat all of it, though, or you're charged for what you don't eat.  The food itself is delicious! I will say the tuna has a slightly metallic taste, and the eel came real chewy (though I'm sure this is an authentic taste). No rolls were shorted their fair share of meat, they were good and big specialty rolls.  I did have to ask for the check and for refills, the wait staff is the only thing I believe the place could improve upon. Also, if you care, the sodas come out in a can and a glass of ice, no fountain drinks.  Overall great experience, will go every time I visit Chicago!

I've been to Kyoto and Okinawa, tasting the freshest of yellow tail, red snapper, tuna, etc. sushi and sashimi... those were the days that made my palette cry joyfully. when me and my friend Leanna partook yesterday, the nostalgia kicked in and I almost cried. it was love struck into every slice and mold.

The $20 all-you-can-eat buffet was a very good deal. They make it as you order, instead of having a bunch of raw sushi sitting on tables like you would expect at a regular buffet. The service was pretty good and the chefs were fast; I only had to wait about 5 minutes to get my first plate. Some of the "fancier" rolls had a bit more rice than normal (and slightly less fish), but they still tasted great. In total, I ate about 5 or 6 rolls and left with a full stomach - something that would normally cost a LOT more than $20 at a regular sushi place.
